msy or coarse fellow. Compare   Bruss  .","Slovenian: from an old dialect short form of the personal name <i>Ambrož</i> (see   Ambrose  ). Compare   Bruss  .","French: topographic name for someone living on a heath, from Occitan <i>brusc</i> ‘heather’, or a habitational name from (Le/Les) Brus, the name of several places in southern France."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Eldor, Reinhard, Rudie, Wilhelm.","German (also <b>Brüss</b>): from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Ambrosius</i> (see   Ambrose  ).","Americanized or Germanized form of Polish, Slovenian, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic)   Brus  , meaning ‘whetstone’ and, as a Slovenian name, also ‘Ambrose’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Brus was born before 1094, in Branston, Leicestershire, England as the daughter of Robert le Brus and Agnes Basset. She married Walter de Eyncourt about 1130. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"before 1094–":"enne 1094–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1100–1168":"1100–1168","1132–1183":"1132–1183","1134–1141":"1134–1141","1136–Male":"1136–Surnud","1066–1094":"1066–1094","–Female":"Surnud","1066":"1066","1132":"1132","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1183":"1183","1094":"1094","1106":"1106","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","about 1132":"umbes 1132","before 1094":"enne 1094","about 1086":"umbes 1086","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Europe":"Europe","Branston, Leicestershire, England":"Branston, Leicestershire, England","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"before 1094–":"ennen vuotta 1094–Kuollut","1094–Female":"1094–Kuollut","1100–1168":"1100–1168","1132–1183":"1132–1183","1134–1141":"1134–1141","1136–Male":"1136–Kuollut","1066–1094":"1066–1094","–Female":"Kuollut","1066":"1066","1132":"1132","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1183":"1183","1094":"1094","1106":"1106","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","about 1132":"noin 1132","before 1094":"ennen vuotta 1094","about 1086":"noin 1086","about 1130":"noin 1130","Europe":"Europe","Branston, Leicestershire, England":"Branston, Leicestershire, England","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"before 1094–":"avant 1094–Décédée","1094–Female":"1094–Décédée","1100–1168":"1100–1168","1132–1183":"1132–1183","1134–1141":"1134–1141","1136–Male":"1136–Décédé"